      <section xml:id="sect-intro-lines">
        <title>Linear functions</title>


		<p>
			The idea of a function is central to most of mathematics - a function carefully explains how two quantities<fn>		<p>
			In reality, or in applications we sometimes need to relate more than two quantities, though we probably won’t get into that this semester.
		</p></fn> are related. We can, describe these relationships
		</p>

		<p><ul>	<li><p>with words,</p></li>
	<li><p>with sketches or graphs,</p></li>
	<li><p>with data, or</p></li>
	<li><p>with (algebraic) formulas.</p></li>

		</ul></p>

		<p>
			What functions do you know <q>by name</q>? We’ll see more of these later, but for the moment, ask yourself if you can pair a formula or a graph with each of those names?
		</p>

		<p>
			You have likely used a variety of formulas and functions throughout math and science classes, research, or work. In math, we typically say something like <me>y = f(x).</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Keep in mind that you use lots of formulas elsewhere with a variety of different letters. We will usually refer to functions as <m>f(x)</m>, but in applications might try to use letters like <m>g = g(w)</m> where we use the same letter for the output variable and function name - this might seem weird, but it’s actually <em>less</em> to worry about and gives more clues about the relationship <em>and</em> how to use it. Before talking more about specific examples and applications of functions, let’s just give an example of relationships between quantities that <em>might or might not</em> illustrate functions and try to recognize what goes wrong.
		</p>

		<p>
			The most important example of a function to start is the linear function. We use these as for a variety of reasons in mathematics and science. You may recall, <me>y = f(x) = mx+b.</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			It turns out, this isn’t as useful as you may have been lead to believe. A more versatile formula is, <me>y = f(x) = y_0 + m(x - x_0).</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Fortunately, these are largely interchangeable, it just depends on what information we have access to as we get started.
		</p>

		<p>
			To start to see how these are connected, what’s something that both formulas have in common?
		</p>

		<p>
			You might be thinking about scatterplots and <q>trend lines</q>, which is a good place to be. That process actually <em>uses</em> some of the calculus we will encounter later. To get started we will be a bit more casual.
		</p>

